## Migration Analysis

Your code has three Thread.Abort patterns:

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---------|----------|-------------|
| **Timeout enforcement** | `thread.Abort()` after `Join` fails | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` |
| **ThreadAbortException catch** | `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| **ResetAbort** | `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(), token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

1. **Cancellation is cooperative, not preemptive.** Unlike `Thread.Abort`, this does *not* forcibly kill running work. If `work()` is a tight CPU loop that never yields, it will keep running after the timeout — the caller just stops waiting. To make `work` actually stop, pass the token into it:

    ```csharp
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;
        var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);
        // ... same as above
    }

    // Caller must cooperate:
    executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
    {
        foreach (var item in items)
        {
            token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
            Process(item);
        }
        return result;
    }, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
    ```

2. **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`.** It holds timers internally — leaking it causes resource leaks. Always use `using`.

3. **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`.** The `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures we only catch *our* timeout, not an unrelated cancellation from `work`.

4. **Uncooperative third-party code** that can't accept a token? Move it to a child `Process` and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout. That's the only safe way to forcibly terminate work in modern .NET.

5. **`Task.WaitAsync`** (new in .NET 6) is the cleanest way to add cancellable waiting. Without it, you'd need `Task.WhenAny(task, Task.Delay(...))`, which is more verbose.
